==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Secularize
<hw>Sec"u*lar*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Secularized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Secularizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧culariser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To convert
from regular or monastic into secular; <as>as, to <ex>secularize</ex> a
priest or a monk</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To convert from spiritual to secular or common use;
<as>as, to <ex>secularize</ex> a church, or church
property</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the Reformation the abbey was <qex>secularized</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Coxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make worldly or unspiritual.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Horsley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secularly</ent>⟦br⟧
